WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.600
So we have three approved Bispecific for multiple myeloma targeting BCMA and then

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:11.220
a couple in the pipeline, a couple that didn't make it, but these are in the relapsed refractory

00:00:11.220 --> 00:00:11.440
setting.

00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:16.920
So we want to know, can we move these up front and exploit the benefits, but understand the

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:22.080
safety concepts related to these bispecifics and the upfront treatment of multiple myeloma?

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:25.260
This is obviously not an exhaustive list of all the trials that are ongoing.

00:00:25.380 --> 00:00:27.700
Look at BCMA bispecifics and multiple myeloma.

00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:32.440
These are the three buckets that I think of with upfront treatment of multiple myeloma.

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:35.820
Transplant eligible as induction, transplant ineligible.

00:00:36.020 --> 00:00:39.840
Now, is this going to be ongoing treatment till progression, or is this going to be time

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:40.540
limited treatment?

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:46.860
And then for the, while it's still on life support, post-transplant maintenance with

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:49.000
Bispecific in the time limited setting.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.520
There's some interesting concepts that we should look at here as well.

00:00:52.780 --> 00:00:56.760
The risks of infections in a patient population that we might have a higher bar for.

00:00:57.560 --> 00:01:03.500
The health of the T cells as these patients will be untreated and how that might translate

00:01:03.500 --> 00:01:05.080
to CRS and ICANN's risk.

00:01:05.580 --> 00:01:11.800
And then should we be demanding more quads for comparator arms in some of the larger

00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:16.560
trials now that we've seen some of the Cepheus and MRAS data supporting that in basically

00:01:16.560 --> 00:01:20.320
transplant and transplant ineligible studies.

00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:24.500
We have some preliminary data from some of the studies that have been presented over

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:25.580
the past couple of years.

00:01:25.580 --> 00:01:27.300
This is the Majestic 5 trial.

00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:33.660
Looking at TEC-based induction therapy prior to transplant, looking at three arms with

00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:41.520
DR plus TEC or DVR plus TEC, followed by transplant, followed by TEC-dera maintenance for 18 cycles.

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:47.820
And the gist of it was that as far as toxicity goes, there was some hematologic toxicity,

00:01:48.020 --> 00:01:50.720
predominantly neutropenia that seemed to be time limited.

00:01:51.580 --> 00:01:54.380
Vortezomib did not increase the risk of this hematologic toxicity.

00:01:55.040 --> 00:01:57.040
CRS occurred at probably about the same rate.

00:01:57.040 --> 00:02:00.360
The same rate that we see in the relapse refractory setting in two thirds of patients, but no

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:02.900
grade three or four CS, no ICANN's occurred.

00:02:02.900 --> 00:02:07.480
There were no grade five AEs and there were no grade five infections or discontinuation

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:08.620
related to infections.

00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:13.900
So we've gotten better at managing the infectious toxicities with prophylaxis and IVIG

00:02:13.900 --> 00:02:14.720
supplementation.

00:02:14.980 --> 00:02:19.840
One of the unique questions in this patient population was how did TEC-based induction

00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:25.740
impact stem cell collection and 96% of patients were able to successfully mobilize for at

00:02:25.740 --> 00:02:26.780
least one transplant.

00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:28.900
And that's what we're looking for in this patient population.

00:02:28.900 --> 00:02:30.660
And that's what we're looking for in this patient population.

00:02:30.660 --> 00:02:34.620
And of course, the response data also brings up a number of other questions because by

00:02:34.620 --> 00:02:39.640
the end of induction, the overall response rate was 100% and the MRD negativity rate

00:02:39.640 --> 00:02:40.500
was 100%.

00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:44.740
So it begs the question, was the transplant even necessary in the first place?

00:02:45.140 --> 00:02:47.760
And I think these data are going to be fleshed out over time.

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:56.520
But as far as we're concerned right now, the TEC-based induction was a successful induction

00:02:56.520 --> 00:02:59.160
regimen and led to unprecedented responses.

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:04.720
With another DCMA-bispecific, the LINC-MM4 trial looking at both transplant-eligible and

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:10.840
ineligible patients, 62% of patients were transplant-eligible, but of them, 10 out of

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:16.020
28 only went on to stem cell transplant, but all had accessible stem cell yield.

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:21.760
The most common toxicities were hematologic with neutropenia infection occurring in 84%

00:03:21.760 --> 00:03:23.880
of patients with 33% grade three.

00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:26.320
This is across both the ineligible and eligible.

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:26.320
So we're looking at a lot of different things.

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:26.360
We're looking at a lot of different things.

00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:26.460
We're looking at a lot of different things.

00:03:26.460 --> 00:03:26.500
We're looking at a lot of different things.

00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:32.580
There's a 44% incidence of CRS, a little bit lower than what is seen with some of

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:38.340
the others, and an 86% overall response rate with patients who received the highest dose

00:03:38.340 --> 00:03:42.620
of Linvo achieving 100% MRT negativity rate.

00:03:44.060 --> 00:03:48.200
And what was different about that trial was that it was monotherapy as opposed to combination.

00:03:49.260 --> 00:03:53.920
There's an ongoing phase three trial with two parts, a dose escalation and dose expansion,

00:03:54.400 --> 00:03:56.400
looking at several different cohorts.

00:03:56.480 --> 00:04:07.200
And with Elra in combination with their rev and the part one with one of the cohorts looking at Elra plus DR was presented recently last year at ASCO.

00:04:07.760 --> 00:04:15.360
And once again, similar theme, CRS occurring in about 62% of patients, but none higher than grade two.

00:04:15.760 --> 00:04:22.920
One grade two ICANS and infections tended to occur early and then waned over time, similar with the other BCMA bispecifics.

00:04:22.920 --> 00:04:25.920
The responses deepened over time with the 97%.

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:26.280
Uh,

00:04:26.280 --> 00:04:30.200
overall response rate and occurred early and maintained over time.

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:43.680
Moving into the post-transplant maintenance setting, the Majestek IV post-transplant using three different arms of Teclen or Tecmonotherapy was presented last year with the safety running cohort.

00:04:43.680 --> 00:04:49.380
And this was also for time-limited therapy with up to 26 cycles.

00:04:49.380 --> 00:04:55.600
Similar themes here, neutropenia occurs early and is generally manageable.

00:04:55.600 --> 00:04:56.100
Uh,

00:04:56.100 --> 00:05:04.260
as one would expect the teclistamab dose intensity was much better than that of the LEN patients had to decrease the doses of LEN due to tolerability.

00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:04.980
Um,

00:05:04.980 --> 00:05:07.440
CRS mainly occurred during the step-up dosing.

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:08.280
And as you see,

00:05:08.280 --> 00:05:10.680
the CRS rate was 40 to 50%,

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:16.380
so maybe slightly less than what we see in the induction setting or in the relapse refractory setting.

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:16.920
Um,

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:19.500
there was no greater signal for infection.

00:05:19.500 --> 00:05:19.860
Uh,

00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:23.580
one patient did pass away from grade five COVID-19.

00:05:24.060 --> 00:05:24.600
Um,

